Model Validation & Training Parameters

This section provides details about how models were trained and validated.

Model Training Parameters

Timeframe Configurations

Timeframe Sequence Length Prediction Horizons (days)
Short-term 30 days 1, 3, 5
Medium-term 60 days 7, 14, 21
Long-term 90 days 30, 60, 90

LSTM Model Architectures

Architecture Description Parameters
Simple Single LSTM layer with dropout LSTM(64) Dropout(0.2) Dense
Medium Two LSTM layers with dropout LSTM(64, return_sequences=True) Dropout(0.2) LSTM(64) Dropout(0.2) Dense
Complex Three LSTM layers with batch normalization LSTM(128, return_sequences=True) BatchNorm Dropout(0.2) LSTM(64, return_sequences=True) BatchNorm Dropout(0.2) LSTM(32) BatchNorm Dropout(0.2) Dense

Training Procedure

  • Optimizer: Adam
  • Loss Function: Mean Squared Error (MSE)
  • Early Stopping: Patience of 10 epochs, monitoring validation loss
  • Validation Split: 20% of data
  • Input Features: Price, Open, High, Low, Volume, Change%, Technical Indicators (when available)
  • Data Normalization: MinMaxScaler (0-1 range)

Validation Methodology

Models are validated using a train-test split approach:

  • Training Period: 8 months of historical data
  • Testing Period: 2 months of out-of-sample data
  • Validation Metrics: RMSE, MAE, R, MAPE

The validation process follows these steps:

  1. Split data into training (80%) and testing (20%) periods
  2. Train models on the training data
  3. Evaluate model performance on test data
  4. After validation, retrain on the full dataset for production use
  5. Models are tested against different prediction horizons to determine optimal forecasting periods
